  "translations": {
    "en": {
      "description": {
        "text": "=General= A bouldering area offering varied climbing on granite. The area was developed in secret during summer 2004 for the SBO 2004 bouldering competition by Dag Knutsson, Urban Duva, Johannes Nilsson, Pär Lindholm, Henke Johansson, Johan Nordlund, Johan Hagberg and Calle Olsson.\n\n=Directions= From central Umeå: Take Gräsmyrsvägen past Röbäck. Pass through the village of Skravelsjö. Turn left onto a small forest road 4 km after Skravelsjö. After 200 m, take the left fork at the first Y-junction. Turn the car round at the turning area just over 1 km from the main road, then drive back 100 metres. Follow the edge of the clear-felled area uphill towards the rock slabs, then follow the path up to the area (about 500 metres).\n\nFrom Skravel: Walk straight downhill from the problem Motorsågsmassakern. About 500 metres.\n\n=Problems=",
        "method": "llm",
        "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
        "sourceIds": [
          "legacy:skravel-2"
        ]
      },
      "sections": {},
      "routes": {
        "skravel-2-problem-1": {
          "description": {
            "text": "Follow the corner left of no. 28.",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:skravel-2"
            ]
          }
        },
        "skravel-2-problem-2": {
          "description": {
            "text": "Between #31 and #32. Sit start beneath the arete from two white-marked pockets, then follow the arete.",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:skravel-2"
            ]
          }
        },
        "skravel-2-problem-3": {
          "description": {
            "text": "The low traverse on the Softish boulder, left of \"Achtung panzer!\". Traverse left and finish up the arete.",
            "method": "llm",
            "model": "gpt-5.6-sol",
            "sourceIds": [
              "legacy:skravel-2"
            ]
          }
        },
        "skravel-2-problem-4": {
          "description": {
            "text": "Big holds, small footholds.",
